#Text=Giovanni Antonio de Carbonariis
#Text=Fr .
#Text=( Brother ) Giovanni Antonio de Carbonariis
#Text=was an Augustinian Friar from Milan who served in London as envoy between the Duke of Milan and King Henry VII .
#Text=He is known to have sailed with John Cabot ( aka Giovanni Caboto ) during his 1498 expedition to North America .
#Text=He may have founded a mission settlement and North America 's oldest , and only medieval , church at Carbonear , Newfoundland and Labrador . [ 1 ]
#Text=History
#Text=Giovanni Antonio de Carbonariis accompanied Francesco Pagano ’s diplomatic mission to London at the start of 1490 , as did Christopher Carbonariis , who appears to have some family connection .

#Text=Jones says that " de Carbonariis " appears to be a family name . Giovanni Carbonariis ' association to John Cabot has been known since the 19th century , based on his letter of 20 June 1498 to the Duke of Milan .
#Text=He said that ‘ Messer Giovanni Antonio de Carbonariis ’ had accompanied Cabot ’s recently departed expedition .
#Text=The Friar had left with five ships provided by King Henry VII of England . [ 2 ]

#Text=The Spanish envoy in London , Pedro de Ayala , wrote to the Crown noting that one of the five ships in Cabot 's expedition had been badly damaged in a storm and was forced to land in Ireland , leaving Cabot to sail on .
#Text=The ambassador notes that on the damaged ship was ‘ another Friar Buil . ’

#Text=This was an allusion to Bernardo Buil , the Minim missionary who had accompanied Christopher Columbus 's 1493 expedition . [ 3 ] Based on limited information , historians thought that Carbonariis was a minor player in the expeditions , and may not have sailed further than Ireland .

#Text=Historian James Williamson had ascertained that Carbonariis was ' a man of some importance ' , having served as an envoy between the Duke of Milan and Henry VII , [ 4 ] but the friar had been overlooked by most historians since then interested in the English voyages of exploration from Bristol .
#Text=Augustinian

#Text=Alwyn Ruddock of the University of London was one of the world 's foremost experts on John Cabot 's expedition and suggested in correspondence that Carbonariis had a more important role , but due to ill health was unable to publish her findings .
#Text=After her death in December 2005 , all of her research notes and materials were destroyed , according to instructions in her will .
#Text=Learning of her research , Dr Evan Jones of the University of Bristol has re-investigated her claims , finding new documents and verifying some of her positions .
#Text=This includes that Carbonariis was an Augustinian friar who had been educated in Pavia .
#Text=In the late 15th century , he was serving as the deputy papal tax collector in England .
#Text=Since his principal , Adriano Castellesi , had been in Rome since 1494 , Carbonariis was in effective control of one of the most lucrative clerical appointments in England .
#Text=In this period , the Church still owned about one third of the land in England , and the Pope took ten per cent of the income generated from that property . [ 5 ]
#Text=Based on his position , Carbonariis controlled institutional wealth and had access to King Henry .
#Text=Fr .
#Text=Giovanni Antonio Carbonariis emerges as a key player in Ruddock 's account of John Cabot 's voyages .

#Text=While she never published a full account , she claimed that he was the explorer 's most important backer in England , having arranged for Cabot to get a loan from Italian bankers in London for an expedition after the Venetian arrived in London in 1495 .
#Text=Even more importantly , she suggests that it was Carbonariis who secured Cabot an audience with King Henry VII of England .
#Text=In March 1496 Cabot and his three grown sons were granted royal Letters patent for westward exploration .
#Text=Ruddock also claims that Carbonariis outfitted a ship , called the Dominus Nobiscum , which accompanied the 1498 expedition .
#Text=The ship carried other Italian friars who , with Carbonariis , are believed to have established a church and religious community in Newfoundland . [ 6 ]

#Text=In his account of this period , historian Richard Hakluyt had mistakenly associated the friars and ship by that name with a 1527 voyage by Cabot 's son Sebastian Cabot ; but , the latter 's ships for that expedition were named Samson and Mary of Guildford . [ 7 ]
#Text=While the religious community in Newfoundland is thought to have lasted at most only a few years , it would have been significant as North America 's first Christian settlement .
#Text=This church appears to have been named after the church of San Giovanni a Carbonara in Naples , which was the mother church of a group of reformed Augustinian Friars called the ' Carbonara ' .
#Text=Dr Ruddock suggested that the community was located at what is now Carbonear , Newfoundland and Labrador , the modern name being a relic survival of the 15th-century settlement .

#Text=( Williamson had already noted a connection between the name of the papal deputy and Carbonear . ) [ 4 ] From 2010-14 archeological excavations were undertaken by Professor Peter Pope ( d. 2017 ) [ 8 ] of Memorial University of Newfoundland in Carbonear to study its colonial history .
#Text=Remains from the 17th into the 19th century were found . [ 9 ] [ 10 ]

#Text=Ruddock 's book proposal and surviving letters to colleagues do not indicate the sources on which she based her claims about the North American settlement , but she had written of discovering more than 20 documents related to Cabot 's voyages .

#Text=Historian Evan Jones has investigated some of her claims and confirmed evidence for a 1499 voyage undertaken by William Weston , a merchant of Bristol ; he is now identified as the first Englishman to lead an expedition to North America . [ 11 ]

#Text=Evan Jones and co-researchers , including Margaret Condon ( University of Bristol ) and Dr Francesco Guidi Bruscoli ( University of Florence ) , are carrying out further investigations of Dr Ruddock 's claims as part of The Cabot Project .
